\i\fs72 \cf5 \cb3 E
\i0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 lmore James was born on a farm in Richland, Mississippi, on January 27, 1918. By the time he was 12, he was playing a one-string, wall-mounted \'93guitar\'94 that was common to the region. The music of Robert Johnson and Kokomo Arnold had drawn him to music. He eventually moved to Jackson, Mississippi, where he ran a radio repair shop and played guitar at night and on weekends. One account has him playing with a band that included drums as early as 1939. If correct, that would place him several years ahead ofMuddy Waters\'a0in blending Delta Blues with electrical amplification and percussion.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i\fs72 \cf5 \cb3 H
\i0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 e was inspired by the local performances of\'a0Robert Johnson\'a0to take up the guitar. It was, in fact, a number by Johnson ("Dust My Broom") that became James\'92 signature song and laid the foundation for his recording career. First cut by James in August 1951, \'93Dust My Broom\'94 contains the strongest example of his stylistic signature: a swooping, full-octave opening figure on slide guitar. His influence went beyond that one riff, however, as he\'92s been virtually credited with inventing blues rock by virtue of energizing primal riffs with a raw, driving intensity.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
